Notice that this can be obtained by replacing formula_9 by formula_79 in the classical expression for kinetic energy in terms of momentum,

formula_83

In the Schrödinger picture, formula_79 takes the form formula_85 where the derivative is taken with respect to position coordinates and hence

formula_86

The expectation value of the electron kinetic energy, formula_87, for a system of &quot;N&quot; electrons described by the wavefunction formula_88 is a sum of 1-electron operator expectation values:

formula_89

where formula_90 is the mass of the electron and formula_91 is the Laplacian operator acting upon the coordinates of the &quot;i&quot;th electron and the summation runs over all electrons.

The density functional formalism of quantum mechanics requires knowledge of the electron density &quot;only&quot;, i.e., it formally does not require knowledge of the wavefunction. Given an electron density formula_92, the exact N-electron kinetic energy functional is unknown; however, for the specific case of a 1-electron system, the kinetic energy can be written as

formula_93

where formula_94 is known as the von Weizsäcker kinetic energy functional.

